How do you think this will impact the morale within the Department of Defen=
se?

It basically calcifies a certain ideology. For instance, if you=E2=80=99re =
a right-wing MAGA guy and you like Christian nationalism and don=E2=80=99t =
believe women should be equal, then the Army=E2=80=99s hiring, and the Navy=
 would love to have you. If you=E2=80=99re trans or a woman, I don=E2=80=99=
t know how you can honestly look at this person and feel confident about th=
eir leadership. What will happen is you=E2=80=99ll see women not wanting to=
 serve in the military. And for sure no Democrats are going to want to serv=
e in the military. It=E2=80=99ll start to look like the Army of the Confede=
racy. It=E2=80=99ll look a lot more like the Army of 1824 than 2024. And in=
 the meantime, the tumult and politicization will be extremely damaging, es=
pecially to the professional corps of officers who are
supposed to be beyond politics.

There=E2=80=99s a lot of general distrust regarding the military industrial=
 complex. Do you think that any of Pete Hegseth=E2=80=99s disruption will d=
o any good for the institution?

Maybe, but at what expense? Removing corruption and tackling the expansion =
of contractors are important issues, and I think, for the most part, bipart=
isan. But using that to cloak the more extreme political and social issues =
is really the game. The language Hegseth uses is intentional; it=E2=80=99s =
populist and effective. He=E2=80=99s a masterful communicator, the likes of=
 which we=E2=80=99ve probably never seen. He may be the least qualified in =
terms of ability to manage it, but he may be the most qualified in terms of=
 his communications dynamism, because he is built for the moment, for Fox N=
ews, for social media, for the podcasts, and all the other places. So it=E2=
=80=99s a really effective move to put in place a very radical person, and =
it=E2=80=99s complemented by
a radical nominee for secretary of veterans affairs as well=E2=80=94Doug Co=
llins, who=E2=80=99s a military veteran, but also a chaplain who=E2=80=99s =
been anti-women and anti-LGBTQ=E2=80=94and they are going to be a one-two p=
unch for executing the MAGA agenda on the two biggest agencies in the feder=
al government.

We can=E2=80=99t afford to have our military politicized. Everything is pol=
iticized nowadays, but the military is supposed to be insulated. It=E2=80=
=99s supposed to be a place where people put the flag above any party. The =
breaking point was when Trump asked General [Mark] Milley [then-chairman of=
 the Joint Chiefs of Staff] to deploy troops in Washington, D.C., and he sa=
id no. If Trump doesn=E2=80=99t have a chairman of the joint chiefs and sec=
retary of defense who stands up to him, and he wants to federalize the Nati=
onal Guard to remove migrant kids from cities, he can do it. So what he=E2=
=80=99s really doing is removing the most important, effective, and powerfu=
l resistance
that he could possibly have. You don=E2=80=99t want our country divided aro=
und our military, and you don=E2=80=99t want our military partisan-ized, an=
d that=E2=80=99s what=E2=80=99s in danger here.

