16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">This kind of arm=
-twisting is unprecedented for a <i>cabinet </i>nominee. It seems to be wor=
king, at least in part: Ernst has come out strongly in favor of one of Trum=
p=E2=80=99s other troubled nominees, <b>Kash</b> <b>Patel</b>, whom Trump h=
as tapped to lead the F.B.I. And it=E2=80=99s made other members wary about=
 voicing their opinions before F.B.I. background checks have been completed=
 and the actual confirmation process begins. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not your=
 incentive to come out publicly and to invite holy hell on yourself,=E2=80=
=9D said a Senate source. =E2=80=9CThat was Joni=E2=80=99s misstep. It=E2=
=80=99s perfectly fine to have issues with these people. Have the meeting, =
look at the background check, have the hearing, go through the process, see=
 how they respond, and make a decision. Push it off until closer to confirm=
ation.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>So far, the =E2=80=9Ccore four=E2=80=9D Republica=
ns who
could potentially tank Trump=E2=80=99s more controversial nominations=E2=80=
=94Sens. <b>Susan Collins</b>, <b>Lisa</b> <b>Murkowski</b>, <b>Mitch</b> <=
b>McConnell</b>, and <b>Jon</b> <b>Curtis</b>=E2=80=94have kept their cards=
 close to the vest. But the chill over the Senate suggests that, notwithsta=
nding certain nominees=E2=80=99 persistent problems, they=E2=80=99re not go=
ing down anytime soon. If Senate majority leader <b>John</b> <b>Thune</b> s=
ignals to Trump that these four members are preparing to say nay, it=E2=80=
=99s possible that Trump will call their bluff by asking for a vote. <br/><=
br/><i>More </i>than four defections, however, would change the calculus co=
nsiderably=E2=80=94particularly if someone like <b>Tom Cotton</b>, the top =
Republican on the Senate Intelligence Committee, were to signal that he has=
 problems with <b>Tulsi Gabbard</b>, Trump=E2=80=99s pick for D.N.I. The sa=
me applies to Senator <b>Jim</b> <b>Risch</b>, the ranking Republican on th=
e Foreign Relations Committee, though he=E2=80=99s stated that he=E2=80=99s
comfortable with all of the nominees. There=E2=80=99s also the matter of ba=
ckground checks=E2=80=94any nominee who doesn=E2=80=99t pass would certainl=
y be more likely to get a <i>no</i> vote. But members are also starting to =
accept that nominees like <b>Robert F. Kennedy Jr. </b>might be the new nor=
mal. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s sort of like okay, let=E2=80=99s take on seed oi=
l,=E2=80=9D the Senate source quipped. <br/><br/>Still, Trump apparently be=
lieves that it=E2=80=99s up to the nominees to earn their confirmations, an=
d he doesn=E2=80=99t think the failure of any one of them would diminish hi=
s own political capital. He=E2=80=99s even happy to rescind nominations and=
 offer them to other candidates with better chances of getting confirmed, i=
f it comes to that. Hegseth certainly didn=E2=80=99t help his own case by f=
ailing to come clean with Trump about his alleged past activities ahead of =
time. <br/> <br/><i>And now, a little more on Hegseth=E2=80=A6</i><br/></td=
